hello guys, quick question on the basics
how do i read the output statevector in ket notation ? Statevector([0.70710678+0.j, 0. +0.j, 0. +0.j, 0.70710678+0.j], dims=(2, 2))(edited)
Anonymous 21-Jul-20 01:06 AM
I don't know if there's a standard way to view the ket notation using qiskit, but if you know your binary, you can convert the statevector into the ket notation pretty easily
1
As an example for a 2 qubit state, the state vector array is some [a0, a1, a2, a3] We can write the ket notation as a0|00> + a1|01> + a2|10> + a3|11>
If you label the elements of the array starting at index 0, and convert the index into an n-bit binary string, you will get the ket notation

The initialize function can be used as this
circuit.initialize( [ amplitude_1, amplitude_3, ], qubit_index, )

Anonymous This what you have written is classical code. But for a quantum computer the measurement happens multiple time in order to plot a probability distribution. There's no way to execute classical code in between two consecutive measurements(atleast the way IBM Q is designed).

>

Anonymous This code actually translates to adding a CX and CZ gate before making the measurement (by the law of deferred measurement, search it up ). That's why this works

Anonymous 22-Jul-20 08:51 PM
counts is a dictionary mapping measurement outcomes to the number of times they are observed. The items() method returns an iterable of key-value pairs as tuples.
2
Anonymous 22-Jul-20 08:53 PM
Thank you Anonymous and Anonymous I'm with you so far Vincent!
Anonymous 22-Jul-20 08:53 PM
The built-in function max has an optional key argument for a function that is applied to each item to get its key for comparison. However, the original value is still returned.
1
(for example, max([1, 2, 3], lambda x: -x) will return 1 because -1 is the greatest key)
1
Putting it together, the max function takes the pairs of measurement outcomes and counts (counts.items()) and finds the one with the highest count (key=operator.itemgetter(1), since (my_outcome, my_count)[1] is my_count).
1

Anonymous 22-Jul-20 09:00 PM
Itâ€™s the same as lambda pair: pair[1]
1
From there, itâ€™s a matter of extracting the measurement outcome from the pair returned from max using [0], then reversing the order of qubits in the outcome with [::-1]. Qubits are conventionally combined in the order q_n q_n-1 ... q_1 q_0 to form a binary number (nth qubit in 2^nâ€™s place).(edited)

why in lab 4, we initialize the last target qubit to |1>, while in lecture all target qubits are initialize to |0>?
2
Anonymous 27-Jul-20 08:32 PM
Anonymous In the lecture, the function f_a,N(x) = a^x mod N is implemented as a gate |x>|w> -> |x>|wâŠ•f_a,N(x)>, while in the lab, it's implemented as |w> -> |f_a,N(w)>. The ancilla bits are not required because f_a,N(x) is reversible if and only if a and N are relatively prime. We know this is the case because N is the product of two primes and we classically check if a is one of those two factors (it's very unlikely for large N) in the first step of Shor's algorithm.(edited)

Anonymous 29-Jul-20 12:57 AM
Spoiler ahead########################################################################################## For solution of lab4, can someone please explain to me the logic/reasoning behind these lines, specially the list part. for x in range(n): exponent = 2**x given_circuit.append(a_x_mod15(a, exponent), [x] + list(range(n, n+m)))
Anonymous 29-Jul-20 01:17 AM
Anonymous You can mark spoilers like this: ||spoilers|| => spoilers
The first bit is a control bit and the rest are target bits. range(n, n+m) creates an iterator with the values n, n+1, ..., n+m-1 (it includes the start and excludes the end). These correspond to the m target qubits following the n control bits. We need to convert the iterator to a list before adding it to a list containing x, the control qubit.(edited)
By the way, the reason we pass a list with one control qubit and m target qubits to given_circuit.append is because these are the inputs required for the gate returned by a_x_mod_15.(edited)

from matplotlib import pyplot as plt import numpy as np from mpl_toolkits.axes_grid1 import make_axes_locatable def get_plot(matrix): fig=plt.figure(figsize=(8,8)) ax1=fig.add_subplot(111) divider = make_axes_locatable(ax1) cax = divider.append_axes('right', size='5%', pad=0.05) im = ax1.imshow(matrix, cmap="Blues", vmin=-1,vmax=1) fig.colorbar(im, cax=cax, orientation='vertical') for (j,i),label in np.ndenumerate(matrix): try: if label<0: ax1.text(i,j,float(str(label)[:6]),ha='center',va='center') else: ax1.text(i,j,float(str(label)[:5]),ha='center',va='center') except: ax1.text(i,j,label,ha='center',va='center') plt.show()
